Lastly, the ethyl and propyl alkyl groups further contribute to the molecular weight and van der Waals interactions; however, their influence is not as substantial as the aromatic rings or the amine function. We assign a conservative value of +15 degrees for the combined effect of both alkyl chains. Adding up the contributions, we estimate a melting point of +15 (phenyl) + 15 (phenyl) + 50 (bridgehead carbon) + 25 (tertiary amine) + 15 (alkyl groups) degrees above the base melting point of a simple hydrocarbon. Assuming a base value similar to that of benzene (5.5 degrees Celsius), which is a small aromatic molecule, we get a predictive melting point of 5.5 + 15 + 15 + 50 + 25 + 15 = 125.5 degrees Celsius.
